node.text:
The Malaysian Palm Oil Association (MPOA) has dismissed any heavy impact of the European Union‚Äôs (EU) ban on local producers, saying there are still other markets available.

Speaking to Malay Mail, MPOA chief executive Datuk Nageeb Wahab said MPOA and its members are instead feeling upbeat over the increased demand for palm oil in the domestic market for both Malaysia and Indonesia. ‚ÄúThe concerns of EU not buying palm oil from Malaysia has all been addressed by the increased of local consumption. We are not unduly worried it as this is a zero-sum game,‚Äù Malaysia produces some 19 million tonne metric of CPO on average annually, while Indonesia produces twice as many. 
Producing the edible oil wreaks havoc on the environment, leading to deforestation, habitat degradation, and loss of animal habitat. The World Wildlife Fund estimates that an area about the size of 300 football fields is cleared each hour in tropical rainforests for palm oil production.

Orangutans and Sumatran tigers are at risk of extinction and several others species, including the Sumatran rhinoceros, sun bear, and clouded leopard, are also suffering because of palm oil production.

When you buy something containing palm oil, please check if it was sustainably harvested or avoid it all together. And remember palm oil is in almost everything, from our favourite pizza dough, detergent, lipstick, chocolate, too biodiesel. Most of these products contain palm oil, thus making the sellers so arrogantly confident. 
But collectively as a whole, if we all shopped sustainably and responsibly we could shake that conference.

This is by far not my best or favourite painting, but for sure a pretty meaningful one. It sums up my emotions when i think about climate change and pollution. Once we forget about our daily struggles and see the bigger picture we should realize that the future of our mankind is at stake. The outcome of our daily behavior will effect our children and grandchildren. And even us right now, if you haven't noticed the multiple catastrophes that happened everywhere on this planet just in this past year. We have the power to change. By simply saving energy or consuming products not packed fully in plastic, by stopping to eat ridicoulus amounts of meat, by taking the bus instead of the car, by wearing clothing multiple seasons instead of falling for fast fashion trends. When we change, politics will change. If politics change, laws change and so on. It starts with us. So lets save this wonderful planet.

The RCM uses a trio of satellites to take daily scans of our country and its waters, collecting invaluable information. This important data helps captains safely navigate through Arctic waters, farmers maximize their crop yields, first responders save lives, and more.
